# Accessibility — build for non-sighted play

Warp must be fully usable with a screen reader and keyboard alone. Treat this as
a functional requirement, not polish. When adding or changing UI:

## Announce dynamic game/app state
- Import `useAnnounce()` from `apps/Warp12/src/a11y/live-announcer` and announce
  events a sighted player would see: turn changes, tiles played, draws, beacons,
  round/match results, errors.
- `polite` for routine narration; `assertive` only for time-critical events
  (your turn, illegal move). Never put game state in visuals alone.

## Names, roles, structure
- Every interactive control has an accessible name. Icon/emoji-only buttons need
  `aria-label` (or `role="img"` + `aria-label` for non-interactive markers);
  decorative emoji get `aria-hidden`.
- Never convey meaning by color, emoji, or position alone — add text or an
  `aria-label`/`aria-describedby`.
- Use semantic elements: `<button>` for actions, `<main>/<nav>`, real headings,
  `<table>` with `<th>`, lists for lists.

## Keyboard & focus
- All actions reachable and operable by keyboard (no hover-only or pointer-only).
- Dialogs: `role="dialog"` + `aria-modal`, labelled by their title, trap focus,
  return focus to the trigger on close, close on Escape.
- Provide visible `:focus-visible` styling.

## Tooltips
- Prefer the portal tooltip pattern (see `ReceiptModRow`/`PortalTip` in
  `bridge-table.tsx`): keyboard-focusable, Escape-dismissable, text also exposed
  via `aria-label`/`aria-describedby`, bubble `aria-hidden`. Avoid native `title`
  (invisible in the Tauri webview, inconsistently announced).

## Hidden-but-announced text
- Use the global `.sr-only` class (in `styles.scss`) for visually-hidden text.
  Do not use `display:none`/`visibility:hidden` for content meant for readers.

When you touch a component, leave it at least as accessible as you found it.
